-'''Donna Hylton''' (born October 29, 1964) is a [[Jamaican Americans|Jamaican-American]]&lt;ref name=WaPo20Jul2018>{{cite news|last=Sheehan|first=Susan|date=July 20, 2018|title=Does sexual abuse early in life justify later misdeeds? The case of Donna Hylton.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/does-sexual-abuse-early-in-life-justify-later-misdeeds-the-case-of-donna-hylton/2018/07/19/f6048bb8-4bef-11e8-84a0-458a1aa9ac0a_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=October 26, 2018}}&lt;/ref> convicted of [[Murder_(United_States_law)#Degrees|murder in the second degree]] and two counts of [[Kidnapping in the United States|kidnapping in the first degree]]&lt;ref name=nysdoccs/> for her role in the kidnapping, rape&lt;ref name=Psych1>{{cite web|title=Crime and Punishment?|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/articles/199507/crime-and-punishment|last=Neimark|first=Jill|work=[[Psychology Today]]|date=July 1, 1995|accessdate=January 23, 2017}}&lt;/ref>, torture and murder of New York businessman Thomas Vigliarolo in 1985.&lt;ref name=NYTimes8Apr1985>{{cite news|date=April 8, 1985|title=7 Held in Slaying of Man in Trunk|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/04/08/nyregion/the-city-7-held-in-slaying-of-man-in-trunk.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=October 26, 2018}}&lt;/ref> Sentenced to 25 years to life, Hylton was paroled in 2012 after serving more than 26 years.&lt;ref name=WaPo20Jul2018/> She is the author of the memoir ''A Little Piece of Light''.&lt;ref name=Kirkus>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/donna-hylton/a-little-piece-of-light/ Kirkus Reviews]&lt;/ref>
+'''Donna Hylton''' (born October 29, 1964) is a [[Jamaican Americans|Jamaican-American]]&lt;ref name=WaPo20Jul2018>{{cite news|last=Sheehan|first=Susan|date=July 20, 2018|title=Does sexual abuse early in life justify later misdeeds? The case of Donna Hylton.|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/outlook/does-sexual-abuse-early-in-life-justify-later-misdeeds-the-case-of-donna-hylton/2018/07/19/f6048bb8-4bef-11e8-84a0-458a1aa9ac0a_story.html|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=October 26, 2018}}&lt;/ref> convicted of a brutal [[Murder_(United_States_law)#Degrees|murder in the second degree]] and two counts of [[Kidnapping in the United States|kidnapping in the first degree]]&lt;ref name=nysdoccs/> for her role in the kidnapping, rape&lt;ref name=Psych1>{{cite web|title=Crime and Punishment?|url=https://www.psychologytoday.com/articles/199507/crime-and-punishment|last=Neimark|first=Jill|work=[[Psychology Today]]|date=July 1, 1995|accessdate=January 23, 2017}}&lt;/ref>, torture and murder of New York businessman Thomas Vigliarolo in 1985.&lt;ref name=NYTimes8Apr1985>{{cite news|date=April 8, 1985|title=7 Held in Slaying of Man in Trunk|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/04/08/nyregion/the-city-7-held-in-slaying-of-man-in-trunk.html|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=October 26, 2018}}&lt;/ref> Sentenced to 25 years to life, Hylton was paroled in 2012 after serving more than 26 years.&lt;ref name=WaPo20Jul2018/> She is the author of the memoir ''A Little Piece of Light''.&lt;ref name=Kirkus>[https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/donna-hylton/a-little-piece-of-light/ Kirkus Reviews]&lt;/ref>

